1307","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1325":"1325","1259":"1259","1322":"1322","28 September 1322":"28 September 1322","1354":"1354","1332":"1332","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","1375":"1375","1287":"1287","1307":"1307","Greifenberg, Brandenburg Preussen, Gryfice, Cryfice County, West Pomeranian, Vopvodeship, Poland":"Gryfice, West Pomerania, Poland","Deutschland":"Germany","Poland":"Poland","Muhldorf, Bavaria, Germany":"Mühldorf, Bavaria, Germany","Germany":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Margarethe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  